<font color="#FF0000">OPEN LETTER TO MARC WEISS</font><br>
<tt>Tue Apr 22 18:18:58 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Dear Marc,<br><br>
I had told the &quot;regulars&quot; that I have no faith that this site was going to endure past your target date. I had told myself that I was not going to stick around and watch the Fall of Saigon once again. Does that date sound familiar to you? It will be the anniversary of the Fall of Saigon, April 30, 1975, in which you may have to pull the plug on this site.<br><br>
Where were you on that date? Do you remember what you were doing on that particular day or those days proceeding the thirtieth? I do. And I am sure many, many vets remember as well. I was in my living room, watching on TV, the chaos in the streets, the ARVN troops moving north to try to protect the city, while an exodus of civilians were moving southbound. I watched as crowds of people pressed against the gates of the embassy as though trying to squeeze through the bars so to get a chance at leaving the country. I saw a woman, with one arm holding her baby up, up over her head, as I saw her calling, screaming as I imagined her begging/pleading for someone to take her baby.<br><br>
I remember the choppers coming and going, from the rooftop of the building and then I saw from the ship, the choppers unloading their precious cargo, only to be tipped over the side to their watery grave.<br><br>
And I doubt that any vet will forget the scene where it was known that there was only one bird left, the last to leave the building, the chance for further evacuation gone. The lowering of the flag for the last time and it being carried to that bird.<br><br>
And do you remember what you felt as all this transpired thanks to the mircle of TV? I remember the knot in my gut thinking that it was all over, thinking about those that I worked on as a medic, those that died, those that I had tagged, it was all for nothing, gone, nothing. And what was going to happen to all those people, those who befriended us, those asked for our help, those who had worked for us,and I envisioned the slaughter of thousands, nay, tens of thousands that we had abandoned there, and thought, what about those kids, those amerasian children, those children whose fathers long gone from the country, and what was to become of them? And my mind keeps going back to those in your unit oh, so, many years before, whose bodies or parts of, returned home but whose souls remained in-country, and the you realized that the ones who did not come home because you couldn't find him or even a part of him, were never coming home, and the one thin hope you had was that someone will stumble across him or his remains, but that hope was now gone, there would be no one to greet him and show him the way home.<br><br>
And I sat there in my living room, and realize that the house was engulf in total darkness except for the test pattern on the TV set to shine any light, that hours had passed without your notice, just as the years had past without your notice and there was no denying that the war was over. The south had lost. So many dead, no one cares, no one remembers, Maya Lin was a glint in no one's eye. No monuments for the fallen, no rememerences of the lost. It was over. It was over. It was over.<br><br>
And if I only knew.<br><br>
And, here we are, the reminents of a dying generation, dying but only partially forgotten thanks to the likes of Maya Lin. A ragtag of burnt out vets along with a smattering of ex-protesters doing what they to save this site from the enevitable. What was once a proud battalion that graced these threads with words, heart, blood and tears, is now a decimated squad.<br><br>
And when this site is silence, we will, once again, have no voice.<br><br>
Maybe it is fitting that this site closes on April 30, on the twenty second anniversary of the Fall of Saigon.  Maybe we will finally be able to forget if we ju don't talk about it. Maybe, but it didn't work before. Someone, on one of these very threads, proclaimed, &quot;It's Over!&quot;. That person was wrong. It's not over til the last one is dead.<br><br>
Should the site clos, Marc, I would like to thank you from the bottom of my heart.  It was short-lived, but better than what we had before.<br><br>
And whom am I kidding. I will be right here, in front of this tube, just like twenty-two years ago,to watch the lights go out.<br>

